[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:scapegoat-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] In computer science, a **scapegoat tree** is a self-balancing binary search tree, invented by Arne Andersson in 1989 and again by Igal Galperin and Ronald L.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] It provides worst-case ${\color {Blue}O(\log n)}$ lookup time (with n as the number of entries) and $O(\log n)$ amortized insertion and deletion time.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Unlike most other self-balancing binary search trees which also provide worst case $O(\log n)$ lookup time, scapegoat trees have no additional per-node memory overhead compared to a regular binary search tree: besides key and value, a node stores only two pointers to the child nodes.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This makes scapegoat trees easier to implement and, due to data structure alignment, can reduce node overhead by up to one-third.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Instead of the small incremental rebalancing operations used by most balanced tree algorithms, scapegoat trees rarely but expensively choose a "scapegoat" and completely rebuilds the subtree rooted at the scapegoat into a complete binary tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Thus, scapegoat trees have $O(n)$ worst-case update performance.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] A binary search tree is said to be weight-balanced if half the nodes are on the left of the root, and half on the right.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Even a degenerate tree (linked list) satisfies this condition if α=1, whereas an α=0.5 would only match almost complete binary trees.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] By contraposition, a tree that is not α-height-balanced is not α-weight-balanced.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Violations of this height balance condition can be detected at insertion time, and imply that a violation of the weight balance condition must exist.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This makes scapegoat trees similar to red–black trees in that they both have restrictions on their height.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] They differ greatly though in their implementations of determining where the rotations (or in the case of scapegoat trees, rebalances) take place.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Whereas red–black trees store additional 'color' information in each node to determine the location, scapegoat trees find a **scapegoat** which isn't α-weight-balanced to perform the rebalance operation on.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This is loosely similar to AVL trees, in that the actual rotations depend on 'balances' of nodes, but the means of determining the balance differs greatly.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Since AVL trees check the balance value on every insertion/deletion, it is typically stored in each node; scapegoat trees are able to calculate it only as needed, which is only when a scapegoat needs to be found.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Unlike most other self-balancing search trees, scapegoat trees are entirely flexible as to their balancing.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] They support any α such that 0.5 < α < 1.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] A high α value results in fewer balances, making insertion quicker but lookups and deletions slower, and vice versa for a low α.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Therefore in practical applications, an α can be chosen depending on how frequently these actions should be performed.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Lookup is not modified from a standard binary search tree, and has a worst-case time of $O(\log n)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This is in contrast to splay trees which have a worst-case time of $O(n)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] The reduced node memory overhead compared to other self-balancing binary search trees can further improve locality of reference and caching.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Insertion is implemented with the same basic ideas as an unbalanced binary search tree, however with a few significant changes.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] When finding the insertion point, the depth of the new node must also be recorded.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This is implemented via a simple counter that gets incremented during each iteration of the lookup, effectively counting the number of edges between the root and the inserted node.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] If this node violates the α-height-balance property (defined above), a rebalance is required.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] To rebalance, an entire subtree rooted at a **scapegoat** undergoes a balancing operation.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] The scapegoat is defined as being an ancestor of the inserted node which isn't α-weight-balanced.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] There will always be at least one such ancestor.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Rebalancing any of them will restore the α-height-balanced property.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] One way of finding a scapegoat, is to climb from the new node back up to the root and select the first node that isn't α-weight-balanced.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Climbing back up to the root requires $O(\log n)$ storage space, usually allocated on the stack, or parent pointers.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This can actually be avoided by pointing each child at its parent as you go down, and repairing on the walk back up.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] To determine whether a potential node is a viable scapegoat, we need to check its α-weight-balanced property.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] However a large optimization can be made by realizing that we already know two of the three sizes, leaving only the third to be calculated.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Consider the following example to demonstrate this.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Where x = this node, x + 1 = parent and size(sibling) is the only function call actually required.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Once the scapegoat is found, the subtree rooted at the scapegoat is completely rebuilt to be perfectly balanced.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This can be done in $O(n)$ time by traversing the nodes of the subtree to find their values in sorted order and recursively choosing the median as the root of the subtree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] As rebalance operations take $O(n)$ time (dependent on the number of nodes of the subtree), insertion has a worst-case performance of $O(n)$ time.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] However, because these worst-case scenarios are spread out, insertion takes $O(\log n)$ amortized time.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Scapegoat trees are loosely height balanced, having a height of at most $\lfloor \log _{1/\alpha }n\rfloor$ , which is $O(\log n)$ by 0.5 < α < 1.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] The cost of finding the insertion point and placing the node is bounded by the height, which is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Following the insertion, there may be a rebalancing that can cost up to $O(n)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] We will now show that the cost of rebalancing is amortized $O(\log n)$ per insertion.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Define the Imbalance of a node *v* to be the absolute value of the difference in size between its left node and right node minus 1, or 0, whichever is greater.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Additionally, we define the imbalance of a subtree to be the sum of the imbalance of the nodes in the subtree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] By definition, the scapegoat node is not α-weight-balanced, thus a child subtree has size at least $\alpha |v|$ , and the sibling subtree has size at most $(1-\alpha )|v|$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Thus, the imbalance of the subtree rooted at v is also $\Omega (|V|)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] The rebuilt tree is perfectly balanced, such that the size of subtrees rooted at the same level differ by at most 1.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] By the above definition of imbalance, the imbalance of all nodes in the subtree is then 0.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Every insertion can introduce at most 1 unit of imbalance into all subtrees containing it.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] The inserted node can only be in at most 1 subtree per level of the tree, meaning the number of subtrees including it is bounded by the height of the tree, which is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Scapegoat trees are unusual in that deletion is easier than insertion.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] To enable deletion, scapegoat trees need to store an additional value with the tree data structure.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This property, which we will call MaxNodeCount simply represents the highest achieved NodeCount.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] It is set to NodeCount whenever the entire tree is rebalanced, and after insertion is set to max(MaxNodeCount, NodeCount).
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] then we rebalance the entire tree about the root, remembering to set MaxNodeCount to NodeCount.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] This gives deletion a worst-case performance of $O(n)$ time, whereas the amortized time is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Suppose the scapegoat tree has n elements and has just been rebuilt (in other words, it is a complete binary tree).
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] At most $n/2-1$ deletions can be performed before the tree must be rebuilt.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] Each of these deletions take $O(\log n)$ time (the amount of time to search for the element and flag it as deleted).
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] The $n/2$ deletion causes the tree to be rebuilt and takes $O(\log n)+O(n)$ (or just $O(n)$ ) time.
[src:scapegoat-tree/scapegoat-tree] The name **Scapegoat tree** *"[...] is based on the common wisdom that, when something goes wrong, the first thing people tend to do is find someone to blame (the scapegoat)."* In the Bible, a scapegoat is an animal that is ritually burdened with the sins of others, and then driven away.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **self-balancing binary search tree** (BST) is any node-based binary search tree that automatically keeps its height (maximal number of levels below the root) small in the face of arbitrary item insertions and deletions.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These operations when designed for a self-balancing binary search tree, contain precautionary measures against boundlessly increasing tree height, so that these abstract data structures receive the attribute "self-balancing".
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For **height-balanced** binary trees, the height is defined to be logarithmic $O(\log n)$ in the number n of items.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] This is the case for many binary search trees, such as AVL trees and red–black trees.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Splay trees and treaps are self-balancing but not height-balanced, as their height is not guaranteed to be logarithmic in the number of items.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees provide efficient implementations for mutable ordered lists, and can be used for other abstract data structures such as associative arrays, priority queues and sets.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Most operations on a binary search tree (BST) take time directly proportional to the height of the tree, so it is desirable to keep the height small.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In other words, the minimum height of a binary tree with *n* nodes is log2(*n*), rounded down; that is, $\lfloor \log _{2}n\rfloor$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, the simplest algorithms for BST item insertion may yield a tree with height *n* in rather common situations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, when the items are inserted in sorted key order, the tree degenerates into a linked list with *n* nodes.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] The difference in performance between the two situations may be enormous: for example, when *n* = 1,000,000, the minimum height is $\lfloor \log _{2}(1,000,000)\rfloor =19$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] If the data items are known ahead of time, the height can be kept small, in the average sense, by adding values in a random order, resulting in a random binary search tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, there are many situations (such as online algorithms) where this randomization is not viable.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary trees solve this problem by performing transformations on the tree (such as tree rotations) at key insertion times, in order to keep the height proportional to log2(*n*).
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Although a certain overhead is involved, it is not bigger than the always necessary lookup cost and may be justified by ensuring fast execution of all operations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] While it is possible to maintain a BST with minimum height with expected $O(\log n)$ time operations (lookup/insertion/removal), the additional space requirements required to maintain such a structure tend to outweigh the decrease in search time.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For comparison, an AVL tree is guaranteed to be within a factor of 1.44 of the optimal height while requiring only two additional bits of storage in a naive implementation.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Therefore, most self-balancing BST algorithms keep the height within a constant factor of this lower bound.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In the asymptotic ("Big-O") sense, a self-balancing BST structure containing *n* items allows the lookup, insertion, and removal of an item in $O(\log n)$ worst-case time, and ordered enumeration of all items in $O(n)$ time.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For some implementations these are per-operation time bounds, while for others they are amortized bounds over a sequence of operations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These times are asymptotically optimal among all data structures that manipulate the key only through comparisons.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees can be used in a natural way to construct and maintain ordered lists, such as priority queues.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] They can also be used for associative arrays; key-value pairs are simply inserted with an ordering based on the key alone.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In this capacity, self-balancing BSTs have a number of advantages and disadvantages over their main competitor, hash tables.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One advantage of self-balancing BSTs is that they allow fast (indeed, asymptotically optimal) enumeration of the items *in key order*, which hash tables do not provide.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One disadvantage is that their lookup algorithms get more complicated when there may be multiple items with the same key.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs have better worst-case lookup performance than most hash tables ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(n)$ ), but have worse average-case performance ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(1)$ ).
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs can be used to implement any algorithm that requires mutable ordered lists, to achieve optimal worst-case asymptotic performance.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, if binary tree sort is implemented with a self-balancing BST, we have a very simple-to-describe yet asymptotically optimal $O(n\log n)$ sorting algorithm.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Similarly, many algorithms in computational geometry exploit variations on self-balancing BSTs to solve problems such as the line segment intersection problem and the point location problem efficiently.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] (For average-case performance, however, self-balancing BSTs may be less efficient than other solutions.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs are flexible data structures, in that it is easy to extend them to efficiently record additional information or perform new operations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, one can record the number of nodes in each subtree having a certain property, allowing one to count the number of nodes in a certain key range with that property in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:scapegoat-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These extensions can be used, for example, to optimize database queries or other list-processing algorithms.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] In discrete mathematics, **tree rotation** is an operation on a binary tree that changes the structure without interfering with the order of the elements.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] A tree rotation moves one node up in the tree and one node down.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] It is used to change the shape of the tree, and in particular to decrease its height by moving smaller subtrees down and larger subtrees up, resulting in improved performance of many tree operations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] There exists an inconsistency in different descriptions as to the definition of the **direction of rotations**.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] This article takes the approach of the directional movement of the rotating node.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The right rotation operation as shown in the adjacent image is performed with *Q* as the root and hence is a right rotation on, or rooted at, *Q*.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] This operation results in a rotation of the tree in the clockwise direction.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The inverse operation is the left rotation, which results in a movement in a counter-clockwise direction (the left rotation shown above is rooted at *P*).
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The key to understanding how a rotation functions is to understand its constraints.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] In particular the order of the leaves of the tree (when read left to right for example) cannot change (another way to think of it is that the order that the leaves would be visited in an in-order traversal must be the same after the operation as before).
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Another constraint is the main property of a binary search tree, namely that all nodes in the right subtree are greater than the parent and all nodes in the left subtree are less than the parent.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Notice that the right child of a left child of the root of a sub-tree (for example node B in the diagram for the tree rooted at Q) can become the left child of the root, that itself becomes the right child of the "new" root in the rotated sub-tree, without violating either of those constraints.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] As seen in the diagram, the order of the leaves doesn't change.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The opposite operation also preserves the order and is the second kind of rotation.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Assuming this is a binary search tree, as stated above, the elements must be interpreted as variables that can be compared to each other.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The alphabetic characters to the left are used as placeholders for these variables.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] In the animation to the right, capital alphabetic characters are used as variable placeholders while lowercase Greek letters are placeholders for an entire set of variables.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The circles represent individual nodes and the triangles represent subtrees.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Each subtree could be empty, consist of a single node, or consist of any number of nodes.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] When a subtree is rotated, the subtree side upon which it is rotated increases its height by one node while the other subtree decreases its height.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] This makes tree rotations useful for rebalancing a tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Consider the terminology of **Root** for the parent node of the subtrees to rotate, **Pivot** for the node which will become the new parent node, **RS** for the side of rotation and **OS** for the opposite side of rotation.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] For the root Q in the diagram above, **RS** is C and **OS** is P.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The programmer must also make sure that the root's parent points to the pivot after the rotation.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Also, the programmer should note that this operation may result in a new root for the entire tree and take care to update pointers accordingly.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The tree rotation renders the inorder traversal of the binary tree invariant.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] This implies the order of the elements is not affected when a rotation is performed in any part of the tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Computing one from the other is very simple.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] There are also *double rotations*, which are combinations of left and right rotations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] A *double left* rotation at X can be defined to be a right rotation at the right child of X followed by a left rotation at X; similarly, a *double right* rotation at X can be defined to be a left rotation at the left child of X followed by a right rotation at X.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Tree rotations are used in a number of tree data structures such as AVL trees, red–black trees, WAVL trees, splay trees, and treaps.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] They require only constant time because they are *local* transformations: they only operate on 5 nodes, and need not examine the rest of the tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] A tree can be rebalanced using rotations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] After a rotation, the side of the rotation increases its height by 1 whilst the side opposite the rotation decreases its height similarly.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Therefore, one can strategically apply rotations to nodes whose left child and right child differ in height by more than 1.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Self-balancing binary search trees apply this operation automatically.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] A type of tree which uses this rebalancing technique is the AVL tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Can the rotation distance between two binary trees be computed in polynomial time?
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] The rotation distance between any two binary trees with the same number of nodes is the minimum number of rotations needed to transform one into the other.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] With this distance, the set of *n*-node binary trees becomes a metric space: the distance is symmetric, positive when given two different trees, and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] It is an open problem whether there exists a polynomial time algorithm for calculating rotation distance, though several variants of the rotation distance problem admit polynomial time algorithms.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Daniel Sleator, Robert Tarjan and William Thurston showed that the rotation distance between any two *n*-node trees (for *n* ≥ 11) is at most 2*n* − 6, and that some pairs of trees are this far apart as soon as *n* is sufficiently large.
[src:scapegoat-tree/tree-rotation] Lionel Pournin showed that, in fact, such pairs exist whenever *n* ≥ 11.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] In computer science, **weight-balanced binary trees** (**WBTs**) are a type of self-balancing binary search trees that can be used to implement dynamic sets, dictionaries (maps) and sequences.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] These trees were introduced by Nievergelt and Reingold in the 1970s as **trees of bounded balance**, or **BB[α] trees**.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] A well known example is a Huffman coding of a corpus.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Like other self-balancing trees, WBTs store bookkeeping information pertaining to balance in their nodes and perform rotations to restore balance when it is disturbed by insertion or deletion operations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Specifically, each node stores the size of the subtree rooted at the node, and the sizes of left and right subtrees are kept within some factor of each other.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Weight-balanced trees are popular in the functional programming community and are used to implement sets and maps in MIT Scheme, SLIB, SML-NJ, and implementations of Haskell.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] A weight-balanced tree is a binary search tree that stores the sizes of subtrees in the nodes.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] By definition, the size of a leaf (typically represented by a nil pointer) is zero.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] The size of an internal node is the sum of sizes of its two children, plus one: (size[n] = size[n.left] + size[n.right] + 1).
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Based on the size, one defines the weight to be weight[n] = size[n] + 1.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Weight has the advantage that the weight of a node is simply the sum of the weights of its left and right children.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Operations that modify the tree must make sure that the weight of the left and right subtrees of every node remain within some factor α of each other, using the same rebalancing operations used in AVL trees: rotations and double rotations.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Here, α is a numerical parameter to be determined when implementing weight balanced trees.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] is a necessary condition for the balancing algorithm to work.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Later work showed a lower bound of 2⁄11 for α, although it can be made arbitrarily small if a custom (and more complicated) rebalancing algorithm is used.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] If α is given its maximum allowed value, the worst-case height of a weight-balanced tree is the same as that of a red–black tree at $2\log _{2}n$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] The number of balancing operations required in a sequence of n insertions and deletions is linear in n, i.e., balancing takes a constant amount of overhead in an amortized sense.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] While maintaining a tree with the minimum search cost requires four kinds of double rotations (LL, LR, RL, RR as in an AVL tree) in insert/delete operations, if we desire only logarithmic performance, LR and RL are the only rotations required in a single top-down pass.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Several set operations have been defined on weight-balanced trees: union, intersection and set difference.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Then fast *bulk* operations on insertions or deletions can be implemented based on these set functions.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] These set operations rely on two helper operations, *Split* and *Join*.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] With the new operations, the implementation of weight-balanced trees can be more efficient and highly-parallelizable.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] The new node may invalidate the weight-balanced invariant.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] , all the subtrees on the left side are merged bottom-up using keys on the path as intermediate nodes from bottom to top to form the left tree, and the right part is symmetric.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Here balance $(x,y)$ means two weights T and T are balanced. expose(v)=(l, k, r) means to extract a tree node T's left child T, the key of the node T and the right child T.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Node(l, k, r) means to create a node of left child T, key T and right child T.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] The union of two weight-balanced trees *t*1 and *t*2 representing sets A and B, is a weight-balanced tree *t* that represents *A* ∪ *B*.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Here, *Split* is presumed to return two trees: one holding the keys less than its input key, the other holding the greater keys.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] The algorithm for intersection or difference is similar, but requires the *Join2* helper routine that is the same as *Join* but without the middle key.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Based on the new functions for union, intersection or difference, either one key or multiple keys can be inserted to or deleted from the weight-balanced tree.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] Since *Split* and *Union* call *Join* but do not deal with the balancing criteria of weight-balanced trees directly, such an implementation is usually called the join-based algorithms.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] The complexity of each of union, intersection and difference is $O\left(m\log \left({n \over m}+1\right)\right)$ for two weight-balanced trees of sizes T and $n(\geq m)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] This complexity is optimal in terms of the number of comparisons.
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] More importantly, since the recursive calls to union, intersection or difference are independent of each other, they can be executed in parallel with a parallel depth $O(\log m\log n)$ .
[src:scapegoat-tree/weight-balanced-tree] When $m=1$ , the join-based implementation has the same computational directed acyclic graph (DAG) as single-element insertion and deletion if the root of the larger tree is used to split the smaller tree.
